<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Phyllodoce breweri </i>is a dwarf, evergreen shrub to 40 cm that forms isolated mats at montane and subalpine elevations. The evergreen leaves are crowded and form a bottlebrush at the end of the numerous branches. They are linearly deeply grooved beneath. Flowers are deep pinkish-rose with stamens exerted beyond the bell-shaped corolla. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance typically occurs in sites that remain moist throughout its short growing season. Stands prefer lake and pond shores, borders of high gradient streams, steep ravines, and avalanche chutes within subalpine forests. They are usually small and limited to snow accumulation areas or moist rocky edges of subalpine streams and meadows. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Calamagrostis muiriana, Vaccinium cespitosum, </i>and other similar alliances tend to occur on flatter terrain and tend to dry earlier in the season. However, all three species present have substantial overlap in stands (Potter 2005). In such cases, the relationships between these three alliances need further evaluation. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
